<div class="post-date">May 24</div>
<h2><a https://yarnetsky.github.io/ontheriversedge/1090.html" title="filibuster deal: could be better, could be worse"> filibuster deal: could be better, could be worse</a></h2>

<div class="entry">


     

  	<p>In the days prior to homework I&#8217;d have known about the filibuster deal immediately. Instead I learned about it nearly four hours later&#8230; I&#8217;m slipping.</p>

	<p>In the world that the Senate should be and has been practiced for umpteen decades, there wouldn&#8217;t be a question about the filibuster. Both parties have used it to keep the wingers out of posts. The filibuster is honorable and a sound way of protecting the minority voice in the Senate. A filibuster allows for individuals in the august body to have their say, yet also puts their entire party on the line.</p>

	<p>If the Repugs wanted to pick on rules to change&#8212;it should be the committee chairman that won&#8217;t even bring a nomination before their committtee. The difference is one person blocking a process versus 40+ senators blocking a process.</p>

	<p>The Democrats should not have had to make a compromise on such a basic tradition. Yet, when you&#8217;re down by 10 votes and the right wingers are hellbent for domination you do what you can do to survive until the next election and hope that one&#8217;s not fixed.</p>

	<p>Still, what president has EVER had 95 percent of their appointees approved? What president or party has EVER had the gaul to assume they&#8217;d get 100 percent approval?</p>



 
<div class="line"></div>

<div class="smallcat">Posted in <a https://yarnetsky.github.io/ontheriversedge/index.html?c=Politics">Politics</a></div>
<div class="smalluser"> by <a https://yarnetsky.github.io/ontheriversedge/index.html?author=E.G.+Yarnetsky">E.G. Yarnetsky</a></div>
